# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Portugal between 10 and 27 December 1820.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] They followed the Liberal Revolution on 24 August.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] These were the first parliamentary elections in Portugal.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] This election aimed to form assemblies in three levels: parochial, provincial, and the Constituent Cortes of 1820.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] Portugal was ruled as an absolute monarchy since 1698, the last time Portugal had any sort of representative assembly prior to 1820.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] While the latter option initially won, the aftermath of the Martinhada (11 November 1820) would lead to the Spanish Constitution of 1812 option being implemented in the 1820 elections.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] The new electoral law was introduced on 22 November and had been directly translated from 1812 Spanish constitution, which had a wide electoral franchise but indirect electoral system.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] All literate men had the right to vote except monks, servants, and some other groups.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] Otherwise eligible men in Portuguese colonies were also allowed to vote.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] In a three-stage process, the electorate directly elected members of parochial assemblies, who then elected provincial assemblies whose members then elected the members of the legislature (i.e., the Constituent Cortes of 1820).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] There were a total of six provinces in mainland Portugal: Alentejo, Beira, Estremadura, Minho, Trás-os-Montes, and Algarve.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] The 110 elected members included 43 jurists and magistrates, 20 academics, 15 members of the church, 11 military personnel, five property owners, three physicians and three tradespeople.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] The vast majority were members of masonic societies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] A second legislative election was held in 1822, the only to be held under the Constitution of 1822.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1820-portuguese-legislative-election] The Vilafrancada (27 May 1823) would bring an end to the 1822 Constitution.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Portugal on 22 November 1822.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] The elections were the only vote held under the 1822 constitution, which provided for a unicameral legislature.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] The Liberal Revolution of 1820 would lead to the 1820 Portuguese elections and to the Constituent Cortes of 1820.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] The Constituent Cortes would approve the Portuguese Constitution of 1822, along with alterations to the electoral system that would be implemented in 1822.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] A two-round system was used, with candidates needing to receive at least 50% of the vote in the first round to be elected; in the second round only a plurality was required.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] All men over the age of 25 were enfranchised except members of religious orders, servants, vagabonds and those still dependent on their parents.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] Men who were married, serving in the military, had graduated from university or were part of the secular clergy were allowed to vote if they were aged 20 or over.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] In comparison with the previous election of 1820, this election would also restrict voting rights to the literate.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] The Vilafrancada (27 May 1823) would mark the beginning of the end of the 1822 constitution and a return to absolutism.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] The parliament held its last session on 2 June 1823, when it approved a declaration against any change to the 1822 constitution.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] Two days later, John VI of Portugal signs a letter declaring that the constitution needs reform and later summons the Portuguese Cortes.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1822-portuguese-legislative-election] The Septembrism movement would reinstate the 1822 constitution (12 September 1836 - 4 April 1838).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Portugal on 8 and 17 October 1826.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] The 1822 constitution, under which the elections that year were held, had been suspended by King John VI in 1823.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] In 1826 John promulgated a Constitutional Charter, which provided for a bicameral parliament, the Cortes Gerais, with an elected Chamber of Deputies and a Chamber of Most Worthy Peers whose members were appointed by the monarch or were members of the nobility.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] The Chamber of Deputies had 138 members; 120 from the mainland, 11 from islands and seven from overseas colonies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] An electoral law was enacted on 7 August 1826, under which members of the Chamber of Deputies were elected from eight multi-member constituencies in which voters had as many votes as there were seats, as well as seven single-member constituencies for the colonial seats.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] The elections used a four-round system, with candidates required to receive a majority of the vote in the first three rounds to be elected, before the fourth round was held using plurality voting.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] The electoral franchise was more restrictive than in 1822, with new income and property requirements on top of the existing age limits, and the elections were held on an indirect basis, with voters electing provincial assemblies, who in turn elected members of the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] To vote for the provincial assemblies, the requirement was an income of 100,000 reals, but only those whose income was at least 200,000 could become members of the provincial assemblies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] Membership of the Chamber of Deputies was restricted to those with an income of at least 400,000 reals.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] The result was a victory for the situationists, although the apostolic opposition boycotted the elections.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] The new Cortes Gerais was opened on 30 October 1826.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1826-portuguese-legislative-election] Although it was due to have a four-year term, it was dissolved on 13 March 1828 by Dom Miguel.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1828-portuguese-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Portugal in May 1828.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1828-portuguese-legislative-election] After Dom Miguel returned to the country in February, the electoral law of 7 August 1826 was annulled by a decree by Miguel on 3 March.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1828-portuguese-legislative-election] The Constitutional Charter of 1826 was suspended, and the Cortes Gerais was subsequently dissolved on 13 March 1828, with the Three Estates was restored.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1828-portuguese-legislative-election] Elections were called to the People's Branch of the Estates and held in May to elect 154 members.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1828-portuguese-legislative-election] The Three Estates met in Ajuda on 23 May, although delegates from Braga, Guimarães and Viseu were unable to attend due to the nascent civil war.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Portugal on 13 and 27 July 1834.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] Following the victory of the Liberals in the Liberal Wars and the accession of Maria II to the throne, the Constitutional Charter of 1826 was reinstated, having been suspended prior to the 1828 elections.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The 1834 elections were held under the same system used for the 1826 elections, with the Electoral Law of 7 August 1826 (annulled by Dom Miguel in 1828) also reinstated.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The Charter provided for a bicameral parliament, the Cortes Gerais, with an elected Chamber of Deputies and a Chamber of Most Worthy Peers whose members were appointed by the monarch or were members of the nobility.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The number of Deputies increased from 138 in 1826 to 143.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The 1826 electoral law provided for an indirect electoral system, in which voters elected provincial assemblies, who in turn elected members of the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] Voting and candidature were restricted to those who met income requirements.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] There were eleven constituencies for the mainland and islands.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The campaign was marred by intimidation and personal insults.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The press was censored and bribery and violence were used to support government candidates.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The opposition Vintistas were unable to campaign in the press, but distributed leaflets, even attempting to gain support from supporters of the deposed Miguel.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The result was a victory for the Cartistas led by José da Silva Carvalho and Agostinho Freire.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] Of the 143 seats, only 119 were filled, with 43 deputies supporting the government, 32 opposing it (led by Manuel da Silva Passos and Saldanha) and 44 independents.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The opposition had won a majority of seats in Porto.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1834-portuguese-legislative-election] The new Cortes Gerais met for the first time on 15 August.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Portugal on 12 August and 12 September 1838.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] A new constitution was promulgated in 1838 following the September Revolution in 1836 and the elections were held based on a decree on 9 April 1838.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] The constitution provided for a bicameral parliament with a directly-elected Senate (replacing the appointed Chamber of Most Worthy Peers) and Chamber of Deputies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] Voting was restricted to men over the age of 25 and income of at least 80,000 reals, although members of religious orders, servants, vagabonds and those still dependent on their parents were barred from voting.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] The voting age was reduced to 20 for men who were married, serving in the military, had graduated from university or were part of the secular clergy.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] Candidates for the Chamber were required to have a net income of over 400,000 reals, and at least half of those elected in each constituency were required to have been born in the area or have lived in it for at least a year.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] Candidates for the Senate needed to be at least 35 years old and had a higher income threshold, but were not required to have a geographic link to their constituency.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] The 142 members of the Chamber of Deputies were elected from 28 multi-member constituencies with between 2 and 15 seats, with 116 representing the mainland, 12 from the islands and 14 representing overseas colonies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] The result was a victory for the ruling Setembristas, who contested the elections in an alliance with their former Cartista opponents as the 'Electoral Association of the Centre'.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1838-portuguese-legislative-election] The Setembristas affiliated with Manuel da Silva Passos were grouped as the 'Public Electoral Association', whilst the Radicals formed the 'Civic Association'.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1840-portuguese-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Portugal on 22 March 1840.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1840-portuguese-legislative-election] The elections were held under the 1838 constitution, which provided for a bicameral parliament with a directly-elected Senate (replacing the appointed Chamber of Most Worthy Peers) and Chamber of Deputies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1840-portuguese-legislative-election] Members of the Chamber of Deputies were elected from 28 multi-member constituencies with between 2 and 15 seats.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1840-portuguese-legislative-election] The result was a victory for the ruling Ordeiros, defeating the opposition Radicals.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1840-portuguese-legislative-election] José Travassos Valdez remained Prime Minister.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] An election of MEP representing Portugal constituency for the 1989-1994 term of the European Parliament was held on 18 June 1989.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] It was part of the wider 1989 European election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] The Social Democratic Party (PSD) won the elections with almost 33 percent of the votes, but lost a lot of ground compared with 1987.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] Although the country was experiencing a significant economic growth at that time, the PSD saw the gap between them and the Socialists narrow to around 4 percentage points.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] On the other hand, the Socialist Party (PS), although failing to topple the PSD as the largest party, performed quite well gaining more than 6% of the votes and polling above 28 percent, compared with the 22 percent in 1987.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] They also gained 2 MEPs, while the PSD lost one.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] The Democratic Unity Coalition (CDU) also performed very well, winning 14 percent and becoming the third political force.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] The Communist/Green alliance was also able to win one more MEP than in 1987.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] CDS saw its share of vote drop a bit, to also 14 percent, and was surpassed by CDU, falling to fourth place.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] Turnout fell dramatically in these election, with just 51 percent of voters casting a ballot.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] The voting method used, for the election of European members of parliament, is by proportional representation using the d'Hondt method, which is known to benefit leading parties.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] In the 1989 EU elections, Portugal had 24 seats to be filled.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal/1989-european-parliament-election-in-portugal] Deputies are elected in a single constituency, corresponding to the entire national territory.
